defaultQ13 default&#xa0; 
defaultAnn defaultMcKechindefault:default This is a question for the whole panel.  There are many examples of UK listed companies in the sector operating primarily in developing nations where there is little evidential basis of benefit to local communities, and there have been issues about employment—the local community may only be in very low-skilled jobs and skilled workers are brought in from other areas—land rights and compensation, and environmental damage.  What do you think we should do here in the 
defaultUK
default in terms of how we manage and regulate this industry, if it is deciding to list its companies here? 
defaultBen Peacheydefault: I will talk from an ICMM perspective.  I should start by saying we are an international organisation, as 
defaultRos
default was saying, that happens to be based in 
defaultLondon
default.  We do not see our role as advising or giving input into the regulatory regimes of Government, but we tend to engage with international initiatives.  
defaultIn part of my answer, I would say one of the biggest challenges that international mining companies face is different legislative regimes.  My simple answer would be to encourage the UK Government in its legislation to partner and work with others through things like the Extractive Industries Transparency Initiative, so that the regulations that companies need to follow are consistent around the world.  That would enable them to do what you want them to do, which is to do a better job and reduce the amount of red tape, i.e. it is the performance improvement that is important
default,
default as much as demonstrating that you are meeting those commitments.  When there is a regulator in the 
defaultUS
default, the EU or
default the
default 
defaultUK
default that is slightly different, that means companies have more work to do.
defaultTo come back to the issues that you mention, it has been shown
default,
default I think
default,
default on both sides that mining, when done well, can have a positive impact on economic growth and employment
default,
default both direct and indirect, as David was mentioning.  It can, without a doubt, have a negative impact on the environment, but also a positive impact on the environment when managed well.  It is important to recognise that as well.  
