default 
defaultEddie Richdefault, Deputy Head, Extractive Industries Transparency Initiative, gave evidence.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ39 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default Good morning and welcome.  Thanks very much for agreeing to address the Committee and answer our inquiries.  Could you introduce yourself for voice transcription purposes?  
defaultEddie Richdefault: My name is Eddie Rich.  I am the Deputy Head of the EITI international secretariat.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ40 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default The EITI was launched in 2002.  What sort of impact do you think it has had over the 11 years?  
defaultEddie Richdefault: It has grown very quickly.  This 2002 reference is not always the most fair representation, because it only became a standard in 2006 and had its international secretariat and board established in 2007.  We have 41 countries implementing it around the world; 25 countries are compliant with the standard
default,
default and the impact in those countries is very varied.  The reasons for them coming to the table are very varied.  What we can say across all of those countries is that there has been a substantial increase in the trust between the Government, 
defaultcompanies and civil society.  That can sound like a bit of a woolly concept, but if you recognise that a lot of these countries are post-conflict—places like Afghanistan, Liberia and Iraq—they are countries that are coming out of very difficult processes, where there is, by its origin, the significant challenge of trust-building in the sector. 
defaultIn addition, you can see, across almost all of those countries, improvements in tax-collection processes.  The process has identified systems in government that need improvement in efficiency of tax collection.  You are also seeing an increase in a level playing field for companies operating there.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ41 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default What does a country have to do to be EITI compliant?  Secondly—I recognise that you are the probably not the most appropriate person to ask this question of—why was this country so slow in signing up to it? 
defaultEddie Rich:default There are two main aspects; the first one is easier than the second.  Each country that is implementing the EITI first has to produce a report of what is happening in the sector from a revenue perspective.  How much money is coming in
default,
default in terms of tax, royalties and signature bonuses?  That is what the Government discloses.  The companies disclose how much they have received in tax, royalties and signature bonuses, and the two are reconciled.  Through that process, it highlights a lot of issues, as I said, about the systems for tax collection.  
defaultUnder the new standard that was launched this year, there are requirements around information on production and a whole load of contextual information on the operations of state-owned companies and so on, which gives a wider picture of the whole operation of the sector along the value chain.  There is the report side, produced in each country every year.  There are about 185 of those reports around the world.  That is the heart of the EITI. 
defaultThe soul of the EITI is the multi-stakeholder group in each country.  This is a national committee of government, company and civil society representatives that sits in each country and oversees the process, decides the scope of the process, and tries to use the information to create a public debate to inform public policy.  That is what the EITI is
default,
default in a nutshell.  
defaultIn terms of why it took so long for the 
defaultUK
default to implement, that is difficult—that is not really for me to answer.
defaultChair:default I was just interested in your perspective. 
defaultEddie Rich:default The one thing that can be said is that the 
defaultUK
default is not as rich in natural resources
default,
default as a percentage of its total GDP
default,
default as many of the countries that were frontrunners with this.  There was some scepticism about the relevance of it then in the 
defaultUK
default.  As the Government saw the relevance across other countries, and they saw that it is not just about the classic resource
default 
defaultcurse issues, they increasingly saw its relevance and the opportunity to send a good signal. 
defaultChair:default We will certainly follow this up with the Minister.  I realise it is the Government 
defaultwho 
defaultshould be answerable on that.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ42 default&#xa0; 
defaultMr Binley:default To help us with the Minister, it is odd this was launched 
defaultwith 
defaultgreat 
defaultfanfare; it was 
defaultproposed by 
defaultBritain
default in 2002 at the World Summit on Sustainable Development.  We all thought it was going to revolutionise the way the mining industry impacted on various countries 
defaultaround the world.  I do not feel from your answer that I have your real view about why the Government did not implement it.  Was it simply because we felt we were the good guys, and the bad guys needed to sign up but the good guys did not?
defaultEddie Rich:default I do not know that that would be exactly how I would put it.  The campaign of Publish What You Pay, which was very much the origin of the EITI process, was focused very much on resource
default 
defaultcurse issues: the relationship between being richly endowed in oil, gas and mineral resources and having high levels of poverty, corruption and conflict.  For many people, that was not the key issue for the 
defaultUK
default.  I can understand the reticence, because if any country is going to implement this, be it the 
defaultUK
default, 
defaultNorway
default or 
defaultAngola
default, they have to have an appreciation of how it will be useful for their own country.  That did take quite a while.  As the EITI has rolled out across countries, people have seen that it is useful for countries, beyond just tackling the classic resource
default 
defaultcurse issues.
default&#xa0;defaultQ43 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default Have you sought statutory powers to force, if you like, the bad boys to comply with the EITI, or do you think there is an international legal process where this approach could be developed?
defaultEddie Rich:default There is a lot of confusion about the voluntary/mandatory issue with the EITI.  It is a process for countries; it is not a process for companies.  In that sense, it is voluntary.  There is no statutory requirement.  It is just like it is voluntary for countries to join the UN.  There is a choice, and when they implement it, if they are going to become compliant with the standard, there is no question that every company and government agency in the country has to report.  If they do not report, the country cannot become compliant.  In that sense, in-country it becomes mandatory.  Some countries have implemented laws to reinforce that.  Others have done it through memorandums of understanding and so on, depending on the need in the country to force the companies and the agencies to comply.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ44 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default I can see the problems in enforcing a particular standard or regulatory regime, and getting a country to adopt it that does not want to.  However, as your chairman, Clare Short, said, “Leaders in some resource-rich countries have chosen to deny their citizens the possibility to see what happens to the money from their natural resources.”  On one level, it would seem quite outrageous that some Governments do not implement this.  Can you see any way internationally that some sort of international regulatory regime could be enforced on those countries?
defaultEddie Rich:default The efforts made around the G20, UN General Assembly resolutions and various other international bodies endorsing the EITI and encouraging countries to do so have been very effective.  Let us not underestimate the 
defaultUK
default and the 
defaultUS
default and other OECD countries saying that they are going to implement it.  That has the massive effect of creating a situation where the EITI for resource-rich countries becomes the expectation and not the aspiration.  We are getting to a situation where the few resource-rich countries that are not implementing the EITI—the 
defaultAngolas
default of the world—do stick out. 
default&#xa0;
defaultQ45 default&#xa0; 
defaultNadhim defaultZahawidefault:default I declare my co-chairmanship of the all-party parliamentary group for the Kurdistan Regional Government.  There is great political upheaval and political change in these countries.  Take 
defaultIraq
default, for example, where you now have a federal system.  The KRG attempted to work with the EITI, because it wanted to be transparent and show where the 
defaultmoney is going
default, yet
default the EITI chose to ignore them and only work with the central Government.  Do you think you need to change the way you behave towards some of these countries? 
defaultEddie Rich:default That is not quite the situation in 
defaultIraq
default.  You are right to say that the EITI is set up at the moment to recognise only countries.  What happened in the case of 
defaultIraq
default is that they produced a report and the board said that they needed to include the KRG, because the money coming into the Kurdish authority was coming into a part of the Government.  However, there was an agreement, which we helped broker, between 
defaultBaghdad
default and Erbil that 
defaultErbil
default would produce a separate chapter within an EITI-wide report.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ46 default&#xa0; 
defaultNadhim defaultZahawidefault:default But you chose to ignore that chapter in the final report. 
defaultEddie Rich:default We did not; the Iraqis did.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ47 default&#xa0; 
defaultNadhim defaultZahawidefault:default Should you not then change the way you deal with these countries, because they are changing in their structures?  That is my point.  You say, “We only deal this way,” but these countries are becoming federal systems, and you should be encouraging transparency, rather than rejecting it on a simple premise. 
defaultEddie Rich:default We did not reject it.  Absolutely, we did not reject it.  What happened was that the KRG produced this chapter, which was extremely poor quality, frankly.  The data did not add up; it did not seem to have any sources.  There was real concern expressed by 
defaultBaghdad
default about the quality of the data.  
defaultBaghdad
default said, “We cannot put this in our report.”
default&#xa0;
